And even if you swore you only took your eyes off that pan of searing steak for just one teeny tiny second, you could end up with scorched pans, caked-on foods, or a greasy mess at the end of your kitchen session. But that grease is no match for you, your soap, or your sponge. Head to our blog for our tried-and-true guide to how to clean the bottoms of pots and pans, no matter how dirty!

At Blue Apron, we recognize the need to source seafood responsibly, ensuring that 100% of the seafood we purchase is rated as either "Best Choice" or "Good Alternative" by The Monterey Bay Aquarium Seafood Watch. We also prioritize sourcing seafood with additional sustainability certifications as best we can, such as Marine Stewardship Council, Aquaculture Stewardship Council or Best Aquaculture Practices, so that the sustainability of our seafood supply chain is third-party verified.

Learn more about why we're involved at our link below! #LetsBlueApron

text:
We all 💙 a scone, but what's the best way to achieve the perfect flaky texture? According to Chef Lauren Katz, it starts by putting your butter in the freezer! ❄️

From Lauren: "You want your butter to be as cold as possible when mixing it into the dough, and the best way to do that is by starting with it right out of the freezer. Grating the frozen butter allows it to keep its texture, and create those flaky layers we all dream about!"

Try Chef Lauren's trick with this week's Cherry-Miso Scones with Sour Cherry Cream! #LetsBlueApron

BLUEAPRON.COM
Cherry-Miso Scones with Sour Cherry Cream

text:
April is 🌎 Month, and we wanted to share some info about how we're working towards lessening our environmental impact. One of those ways is with our award-winning gel packs that keep your ingredients cold until they arrive at your door! Replacing our old polymer ice packs, these gel packs are water-based, and the contents can be safely drained down the sink. Once emptied, the plastic exterior can be recycled via in-store drop off!

Learn more about them at our blog post below! #LetsBlueApron

text:
In honor of #WomensHistoryMonth, we asked some of our Test Kitchen chefs to tell us about their favorite women working in the food space, and how their work has impacted each one of their culinary perspectives. Our final profile comes from Chef Kristen Merris-Huffman who's admiration for Chef Dorie Greenspan] (and her Chocolate-Chocolate Chunk Muffins) goes all the way back to her childhood!

From Kristen: "One of my all-time favorite chefs is Dorie Greenspan because she essentially taught me how to bake. Her recipes are so thoroughly tested, precise and well-written! I have a lot of fond memories of my mom baking Dorie Greenspan cakes for various birthdays growing up and appreciate that she really has a recipe for absolutely everything. I also love that most of her cookbooks have a mix of both more elaborate weekend projects and simpler, easier to follow recipes so there is something for everyone and every skill level!"

A huge thanks to Dorie Greenspan] , and all of the incredible women working in the food space for inspiring a generation of cooks to follow their dreams! #LetsBlueApron

text:
In honor of #WomensHistoryMonth, we asked some of our Test Kitchen chefs to tell us about their favorite women working in the food space, and how their work has impacted each one of their culinary perspectives. This week, Chef Annabel Epstein tolls the virtues of @debperelman and her Chocolate Olive Oil Cake!

From Annabel: "Deb taught me how to cook and feed myself in college, and I would credit her with teaching me how to cook almost anything - her recipes of classic dishes are always foolproof, streamlined, and delicious. One of my favorite recipes of hers is this Chocolate Olive Oil Cake - it happens to be vegan, is one bowl, uses the most basic of ingredients, and tastes like the best version of boxed Devil's Food Cake. I've made it countless times - whether as a base for birthday cake, last minute dessert, or late night cake craving, it always hits the spot!"

*Adds Chocolate Olive Oil Cake to shopping list* Thanks to @debperelman for all of her incredible recipes, and look out for more profiles all month long! #LetsBlueApron

text:
In honor of #WomensHistoryMonth, we asked some of our Test Kitchen chefs to tell us about their favorite women working in the food space, and how their work has impacted each one of their culinary perspectives. First up, Chef Lauren Katz tells us why christinatosi] (and her Burnt Miso Pound Cake) takes her #1 spot!

From Lauren: "My favorite chef is Christina Tosi. I've always admired her playful and nostalgic creativity, and her passion for baking is unmatched. She's smart (hello, mathematics degree!) and eloquent, and you can tell that every recipe she creates stems from so much thought and love. She's helped me discover my love of using savory ingredients in desserts, like miso paste and even curry paste! Plus, her signature Chuck Taylor sneakers, overalls, and bandana headband are test kitchen #goals."

We couldn't have said it better, chef! Thanks to christinatosi] for all of her contributions, and look out for more profiles all month long! #LetsBlueApron

🔥 Make sure your pan is properly heated - you should hear a sizzle when you add your protein!

text:
In honor of Black History Month, we want to highlight some of the incredible chefs and food personalities who are working to shape and develop our culinary landscape. This week, we're focusing on Chef Bryant Terry! Besides being a lauded chef (he's been the Chef-in-Residence at the Museum of the African Diaspora since 2015), Chef Terry is also an incredibly acclaimed cookbook author, with 6 books already under his belt. His latest book, Black Food, went on to be one of the most critically adored books of last year, and an invaluable addition to anyone's shelf.

In his culinary journey, Chef Terry has done an amazing job of bringing vegan cuisine to the masses, and constantly making us challenge ourselves to think outside of the box when it comes to eating. In his book Vegetable Kingdom: The Abundant World of Vegan Recipes, Chef Terry shared a recipe for Caramelized Leek & Seared Mushroom Toast, which feels fancy enough for company, but easy enough for your daily lunch fix. Thanks to Chef Terry for all of his contributions, and for making our world a more delicious place to live in!

text:
In honor of Black History Month, we want to highlight some of the incredible chefs and food personalities who are working to shape and develop our culinary landscape. Next up, Chef Jerrelle Guy! A multi-talented chef and baker, Chef Guy received her Masters in Gastronomy prior to writing her first cookbook, the James Beard Award nominated Black Girl Baking! In her book, Chef Guy shares recipes that tell the story of her life, and hopefully allows you to create your own food memories as well!

Chef Guys is also a popular recipe contributor to various food publications, and her Strawberry Pretzel Pie which appeared in the New York Times perfectly captures the season of summer in every bite. Thanks to Chef Guy for all of her incredible work, and we can't wait to see what she does next!

text:
In honor of Black History Month, we wanted to highlight some of the incredible chefs and food personalities who are working to shape and develop our culinary landscape. First up Chef Alexander Smalls ! A multi-award winner for his work in both food and music (in addition to being a chef, he’s also a classically trained opera singer), Chef Smalls has shared his love for food and culture with his two renowned restaurants in Harlem, The Cecil & Minton's Harlem.

In his latest book, Meals, Music, and Muses: Recipes from My African American Kitchen, Chef Smalls shares a recipe for Smothered Shrimp in Crab-Meat Gravy that's perfect on both your holiday and weeknight dinner table. Thank you Chef for all that you do to continue to educate and share your passion for food - we’re all better for it!

text:
When the weather outside is frightful, make maple snow candy!
It’s an easy, fun, and delicious way to take advantage of the winter season, and comes together in just 3 steps!

❄️ First, boil your syrup in a small pot until it reaches 235 degrees Fahrenheit.

❄️ Next, carefully pour thin lines of the hot syrup directly on the snow (if you don’t want to do this part outside, gather some snow on a sheet pan and bring the party indoors!).

❄️ Finally, press a popsicle stick into the syrup and slowly roll it around the stick. And just like that, you’ve got maple candy! #LetsBlueApron

text:
Health Tip of the Week: More than just fun to eat, snap peas can provide a great deal of vitamins and minerals that may improve your overall health! Snap peas are loaded with Vitamin K, which plays an important part in helping keep your skeletal system strong, as well as potentially helping to prevent osteoporosis! They're also rich in beta-carotene and vitamin A, which are important for the growth of immune cells.

Look for snap peas in this week's Peach & Snap Pea Grain Bowl, a part of our #BAWellness360 menu!

text:
Health Tip of the Week: Roasted, grilled, sautéed or stir-fried, there's countless ways to enjoy one of our favorite proteins: chicken!

An incredible source of protein, adding chicken to your diet may help support weight loss, muscle growth, and bone health! Chicken provides many under-consumed vitamins and minerals, and may contribute to a heart-healthy, low cholesterol diet!

This week, succulent chicken breast pieces are tossed in our bright basil pesto and served over a bed of tender farro - it's everything you need for dinnertime delight! Look for our Italian Chicken & Farro Bowl with Pesto, on this week's #BAWellness360 menu!
